               <msContents>
                  <summary>Part of a letter, circa 1030 CE, from the Jewish
                        community in Sicily, its court and elders (probably the principal community
                        in Palermo), to the Jewish communities in Qayrawān and al-Mahdiyya,
                        specifically addressing Elḥanan b. Ḥušiʾel and Jacob the Nagid b. Amram as
                        heads of the community in Qayrawān, praising the achievements of Ḥayyim b.
                        Jacob the Spaniard (known as Ḵalaf). The letter mentions other individuals
                        including a certain Nathan, Abraham b. David b. Labrāṭ, Samuel b. Moses, Abū
                        l-Faraj, who is on his way to Egypt, Moses b. Yaḥyā the Perfumer, and ʿAmmar
                        b. Joshua al-Ḥalabī (i.e. from Aleppo). Signed by Samuel b. Moses, David b.
                        Levi, Samuel b. [...], Sahlān b. Joshua, Jose[ph] b. [...], [...] b.
                        [...]el, Abraham b. Hayyim, Judah b. Elijah, Elijah b. Jonah, Elijah b.
                        Abraham, [...] b. Jacob, Nissim b. Abraham, Mattitya b. Jon[ah], [...] b.
                        Jacob, Pappos b. Šabbetay, Šabbetay b. [...], [...] b. Judah, Isaac b.
                        Isaac the Cantor, Isaac b. [...]. </summary>
